 fostered the relative decline of U.S. dominance on the world trade scene as the reduction of trade and investment barriers prompted friction and conflict between different kinds of capitalist systems. Identifying the historical and legal issues key to postwar trade policy, Ostry has commandingly charted our economic course through the last half of this century and, perhaps, into the next. "Sylvia Ostry knows this subject as few others do, both as a scholar of international trade issues and a major player in the ongoing negotiations that have created the rules of the trade game. The Post-Cold War Trading System is a fine summary of where we've been and where we ought to be going."—Peter Passell, economic scene columnist for The New York Times  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommercial policy. 0aInternational economic integration. 0aInternational trade. 0aUnited States -- Commercial policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acold war, government, policy, history, economics, politics, education, living standards, growth, economic, international, trade, economy, investment, capitalism, convergence, technology, gatt, east asia, uruguay, multilateralism, nonfiction, development, reconstruction, japan, barriers, dominance, globalization, competition, profit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226637914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226637914/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles